Boil a large #pot of salted water for the @dried linguine{180%g}.

When boiling, add the linguine to the water and bring back to the boil. Cook until softened, ~{12%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #colander and pop back in the pot, off the heat. Drizzle with @oil{to taste} and stir through to prevent sticking.

> TIP: If you're in a hurry you can boil the water in your kettle.

Meanwhile, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}(halved, peeled and thinly sliced).

Peel and grate the @garlic{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a garlic press).

Finely chop the @chives{5%g}(finely chopped) (use scissors if you prefer).

Place a #pan over medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Once hot, add the @prawns{180%g} and onion. Season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw prawns. Prawns are cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle.

Cook until the prawns are pink and the onion has softened, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Add the garlic to the pan and fry until fragrant, ~{1%minute}.

Stir in the @creme fraiche{110%g}, @vegetable stock{1%sachet}, @Italian herbs{1%sachet} and @water{75%ml}.

> Double the water quantity for 4p.

Bring to the boil, then reduce the heat and simmer until thickened, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Add the @baby spinach{60%g} to the sauce a handful at a time until wilted and piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Add the @grated Italian style hard cheese{50%g} and @butter{1%tbsp} and stir until both have melted, ~{1-2%minutes}.

> Double the butter quantity for 4p.

Stir the cooked linguine into the sauce along with half the chives. Season with salt and pepper.

> Tip: Loosen the sauce with a splash of water if required.

== To Serve ==

Share the cheesy Alfredo style prawn linguine between bowls. Sprinkle with the remaining chives. Finish with a drizzle of @balsamic glaze{1%sachet}(drizzled).